[[Image:Potbelly 6.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.7|alt=A low stairway rising to the left from a flat grassy area. The top of the stairway is blocked by thick tropical vegetation.|Takalik Abaj was continuously occupied for almost two thousand years.<ref name="PH05p997">Popenoe de Hatch 2005, p.997.</ref> This photo shows the access stairway to Terrace&nbsp;3, dating to the Late Preclassic.<ref name="Garc<U+00ED>a176">Garc<U+00ED>a 1997, p.176.</ref>]]
[[Image:TakalikAbajBallcourt.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.7|alt=A cleared area of bare soil strewn with rubble, with raised areas to the left and right and roofed with corrugated metal supported by timber poles.|Excavations of the Middle Preclassic [[Mesoamerican ballcourt|ballcourt]] at Takalik Abaj<ref name="SL94p73-4">Schieber de Lavarreda 1994, pp.73&ndash;4.</ref>]]
'''Tak'alik A'baj'''' ([[English language|English]]: {{IPA|[taka'li:k a'bah]}} [[K'iche' language|K'ichee']]: {{pron|tak<U+02C0>a'lik a'<U+0253>ax|Takalik Abaj pronunciation.ogg}}) is a [[pre-Columbian]] [[archaeology|archaeological]] site in [[Guatemala]]; it was formerly known as '''Abaj Takalik'''. It is one of several [[Mesoamerica]]n sites with both [[Olmec]] and [[Maya civilization|Maya]] features.  The site flourished in the [[Mesoamerican chronology|Preclassic]] and [[Mesoamerican chronology|Classic]] periods, from the 9th century BC through to at least the 10th century AD, and was an important [[Trade in Maya civilization|centre of commerce]],<ref>Love 2007, p.297. Popenoe de Hatch 2005, pp.992, 994.</ref> trading with [[Kaminaljuyu]] and [[Chocol<U+00E1>]]. Investigations have revealed that it is one of the largest sites with [[monumental sculpture|sculptured monuments]] on the Pacific coastal plain.<ref>Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.236.</ref> Olmec-style sculptures include a possible colossal head, [[petroglyph]]s and others.<ref name="Love2007p288">Love 2007, p.288.</ref> The site has one of the greatest concentrations of Olmec-style sculpture outside of the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref name="Love2007p288"/>

Takalik Abaj is representative of the first blossoming of Maya culture that had occurred by about 400 BC.<ref>Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.33.</ref> The site includes a Maya royal tomb and examples of [[Maya script|Maya hieroglyphic inscriptions]] that are among the earliest from the Maya region. Excavation is continuing at the site; the monumental [[Maya architecture|architecture]] and persistent tradition of sculpture in a variety of styles suggest the site was of some importance.<ref name="Adams96p81">Adams 1996, p.81.</ref>

Finds from the site indicate contact with the distant metropolis of [[Teotihuacan]] in the [[Valley of Mexico]] and imply that Takalik Abaj was conquered by it or its allies.<ref name="PH&SL2001p993-4">Popenoe de Hatch & Schieber de Lavarreda 2001, pp.993&ndash;4.</ref> Takalik Abaj was linked to long-distance [[trade in Maya civilization|Maya trade routes]] that shifted over time but allowed the city to participate in a trade network that included the [[Guatemalan highlands]] and the Pacific coastal plain from [[Mexico]] to [[El Salvador]].

Takalik Abaj was a sizeable city with the principal [[Mesoamerican architecture|architecture]] clustered into four main groups spread across nine terraces. While some of these were natural features, others were artificial constructions requiring an enormous investment in labour and materials.<ref>Wolley Schwarz 2001, pp.1006, 1009.</ref> The site featured a sophisticated water drainage system and a wealth of sculptured monuments.

==Etymology==
''Tak'alik A'baj<nowiki>'</nowiki>'' means "standing stone" in the local [[K'iche' language|K'iche' Maya language]], combining the adjective ''tak<U+2019>alik'' meaning "standing", and the noun ''ab<U+00E4>j'' meaning "stone" or "rock".<ref>Christenson; Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26.</ref> It was initially named ''Abaj Takalik'' by the American archaeologist [[Suzanna Miles]],<ref>Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26. Note that Miles's first name is given variously as Suzanna (Kelly 1996, p.215.), Susanna (Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.239.) and Susan (Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26.)</ref> using Spanish word order. This was grammatically incorrect in K'iche';<ref name="CassierIchon26">Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26.</ref> the Guatemalan government has now officially corrected this to ''Tak'alik A'baj'''. The ancient name of the site is as yet unknown.

==Location==
[[Image:Larger Southern Maya area v3.svg|left|thumb|350px|alt=Takalik Abaj is located in the middle of the Southern Maya Area. The landmass is bordered by the Pacific Ocean to the southwest, the Gulf of Mexico to the northwest and the Atlantic Ocean to the east, with Takalik Abaj lying near the Pacific Ocean.|Takalik Abaj with relation to the Olmec heartland]]
The site lies in the southwest of [[Guatemala]], about 45&nbsp;km (28 miles) from the border with Mexico<ref name="Sharer467">Sharer 2000, p.467.</ref><ref name="SharerTraxler239">Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.239.</ref> and 40&nbsp;km (25 miles) from the Pacific Ocean.<ref name="CassierIchon24">Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref>

Takalik Abaj is located in the north of the municipality of [[El Asintal]], in the extreme north of the [[Retalhuleu Department]] of Guatemala, some 120 miles (190&nbsp;km) from [[Guatemala City]].<ref>Zetina Aldana & Escobar 1994, p.3. Kelly 1996, p.210. Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref>  The site lies among five coffee plantations in the lower foothills of the [[Sierra Madre de Chiapas|Sierra Madre]] mountains; the Santa Margarita, San Isidro Piedra Parada, Buenos Aires, San El<U+00ED>as and Dolores plantations.<ref name="ZetinaEscobar3CassierIchon24">Zetina Aldana & Escobar 1994, p.3. Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref> Takalik Abaj sits upon a ridge running north-south, descending in a southwards direction.<ref name="Kelly210.">Kelly 1996, p.210.</ref> This ridge is bordered on the west by the river [[Nim<U+00E1> River|Nim<U+00E1>]] and on the east by the river [[Ixchay<U+00E1> River|Ixchay<U+00E1>]], both flowing down from the [[Guatemalan Highlands]].<ref>Zetina Aldana & Escobar 1994, p.3.</ref> The Ixchay<U+00E1> flows in a deep ravine but a suitable crossing point is located near to the site. The situation of Takalik Abaj at this crossing point was probably important in the founding of the city, since this channeled important trade routes through the site and controlled access to them.<ref name="PH&SL991">Popenoe de Hatch & Schieber de Lavarreda 2001, p.991.</ref>

Takalik Abaj sits at an altitude of approximately {{convert|600|m|ft}} above sea level in an [[ecological region]] classed as [[subtropical moist forest]].<ref>Zetina Aldana & Escobar 1994, p.3. Rizzo de Robles 1991, p.32.</ref> The temperature normally varies between 21&nbsp;<U+00B0>C and 25&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (70&nbsp;<U+00B0>F and 77&nbsp;<U+00B0>F) and the [[Evapotranspiration#Potential_evapotranspiration|potential evapotranspiration ratio]] averages 0.45.<ref>Garc<U+00ED>a 1997, p.171.</ref> The area receives high annual rainfall, varying between {{convert|2136|and|4372|mm|in|0}}, with an average annual rainfall of {{convert|3284|mm|in|0}}.<ref>Zetina Aldana & Escobar 1994, p.18.</ref> Local vegetation includes the Pascua de Monta<U+00F1>a (''Pogonopus spesiosus''), Chichique (''Aspidosperma megalocarpum''), Tepecaulote (''Leuhea speciosa''), Caulote or West Indian Elm (''Guazuma ulminofolia''), Hormigo (''Platymiscium dimorphandrum''), [[Mexican Cedar]] (''Cedrela mexicana''), [[Brosimum alicastrum|Breadnut]] (''Brosimum'' sp.), [[Tamarind]] (''Tamarindus indica'') and Papaturria (''Coccoloba montana'').<ref>Rizzo de Robles 1991, p.33.</ref>

A road, denominated 6W, passes the site running {{convert|30|km|mi}} from the town of [[Retalhuleu]] to [[Colomba|Colomba Costa Cuca]] in the department of [[Quetzaltenango (department)|Quetzaltenango]].<ref name="ZetinaEscobar3CassierIchon24"/>

Takalik Abaj is located at an approximate distance of {{convert|100|km|mi}} from the contemporary archaeological site of [[Monte Alto culture|Monte Alto]], 130&nbsp;km (81 miles) from [[Kaminaljuyu]] and {{convert|60|km|mi}} from [[Izapa]] in Mexico.<ref name="CassierIchon24"/>

==Ethnicity==
[[Image:Formative Period southern Mesoamerica 2.svg|right|thumb|350px|alt=Takalik Abaj is situated immediately south of an area of higher terrain, with a wide flat coastal plain to the south. The landmass is bordered by the Pacific Ocean to the southwest.|Takalik Abaj and other Preclassic sites on the Pacific coast]]
The changing styles of architecture and iconography at Tak'alik Abaj suggest that the site has been occupied by changing ethnic groups. The archaeological finds of the Middle Preclassic period suggest that the population of Takalik Abaj may have been affiliated with the [[Olmec]] culture of the [[Olmec heartland|Gulf Coast lowlands region]] who are thought to have been speakers of a [[Mixe-Zoque languages|Mixe-Zoquean language]].<ref name="SharerTraxler239"/><ref name="PH&SL991"/> In the Late Preclassic period Olmec art styles were exchanged for Maya styles and presumably this shift was accompanied by an influx of ethnic Maya, speaking a [[Mayan languages|Mayan language]].<ref name="PH05p996">Popenoe de Hatch 2005, p.996.</ref> There are some hints from the indigenous chronicles that the inhabitants of the site may have been the Yoc Cancheb, a branch of the [[Mam people|Mam]] Maya.<ref name="PH05p996"/>

==Economy and trade==
Takalik Abaj was one of a series of early sites on or near the [[Soconusco|Pacific coastal plain]] that were important commercial, ceremonial and political centres. It is apparent that it prospered from the production of [[Cocoa bean|cacao]] and from the [[trade in Maya civilization|trade routes]] that crossed the region.<ref>Sharer 2000, p.455.</ref> At the time of the [[Spanish Conquest]] in the 16th century the area was still important for its cacao production.<ref>Coe 1999, p.64.</ref>

Study of [[Obsidian use in Mesoamerica|obsidian]] recovered at Takalik Abaj indicates that the majority originated from the [[El Chayal]] and [[San Mart<U+00ED>n Jilotepeque]] sources in the Guatemalan highlands. Lesser quantities of obsidian originated from other sources such as [[Tajumulco]], [[Ixtepeque]] and [[Pachuca]].<ref name="Crasborn696">Crasborn 2005, p.696.</ref> Obsidian is a natural volcanic glass that was used across Mesoamerica to make durable tools and weapons including knives, spearheads, arrowheads, [[bloodletting in Mesoamerica|bloodletters]] for ritual [[sacrifice in Maya culture|autosacrifice]], [[prismatic blade]]s for woodwork and many other day-to-day tools. The use of obsidian by the Maya has been likened to steel use in the modern world and it was widely traded throughout the Maya region and beyond.<ref>Coe 1999, p.30. Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.37.</ref> The proportion of obsidian from different sources varied over time:

