==History==
{{Maya civilization}}
The site had a long and continuous settlement history, with the period of principal occupation stretching from the Middle Preclassic down to the Postclassic. The earliest known occupation at Takalik Abaj dates towards the end of the Early Preclassic, ca. 1000 BC. However it was not until the Middle to Late Preclassic that its first real florescence began with a noted surge in architectural constructions.<ref name="Kelly210.">Kelly 1996, p.210.</ref> From this period onwards a continuity of culture and population settlement is in evidence, as represented by the persistence of a local ceramic style (called ''Ocosito'') that remained in use until the Late Classic. The Ocosito style was typically made with red paste and [[pumice]] and extended westwards at least as far as [[Coatepeque, Quetzaltenango|Coatepeque]], southwards to the [[Ocosito River]] and eastwards to the [[Samal<U+00E1> River]]. By the Terminal Classic, pottery associated with a highland [[K'iche' people|K'iche']] ceramic style had begun to appear intermixed with Ocosito ceramic complex deposits. Ocosito ceramics were replaced entirely by the K'iche' ceramic tradition by the Early Postclassic period.<ref>Popenoe de Hatch 2005, pp.992&ndash;3. Schieber de Lavarreda & Claudio P<U+00E9>rez 2005, p.724.</ref>

